nity in modern Russia, manifesting themselves among both pro-Putin elites and his political opposition. As Borenstein shows, this paranoid fantasy until recently characterized only the marginal and the irrelevant. Now, through its embodiment in pop culture, the expressions of a conspiratorial worldview are seen everywhere. Plots against Russia is an important contribution to the fields of Russian literary and cultural studies from one of its preeminent voices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aConspiracy theorieszRussia (Federation) 0aConspiracy theorieszRussia (Federation). 0aNational characteristics, Russian. 0aParanoiaxSocial aspectszRussia (Federation) 0aParanoiaxSocial aspectszRussia (Federation). 0aPolitical culturezRussia (Federation) 0aPolitical culturezRussia (Federation). 0aPopular culturezRussia (Federation) 0aPopular culturezRussia (Federation). 0aPost-communismxSocial aspectszRussia (Federation) 0aPost-communismxSocial aspectszRussia (Federation). 4aHistory. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  akonspirologiia.  amodern Russia.  aparanoia.  apop culture.  apro-Putin elites.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2019 Englishz978311061036908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2019z9783110606348oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/97815017163